Balancing the benefits and costs of antibiotic drugs: the TREAT model.

Leibovici L(1), Paul M, Andreassen S.

Author information:
(1)Department of Medicine E, Beilinson Hospital, Rabin Medical Center, 
Petah-Tiqva, Israel. leibovic@post.tau.ac.il

TREAT is a computerized decision support system aimed at improving empirical 
antibiotic treatment of inpatients with suspected bacterial infections. It 
contains a model that balances, for each antibiotic choice (including 'no 
antibiotics'), expected benefit and expected costs. The main benefit afforded by 
appropriate, empirical, early antibiotic treatment in moderate to severe 
infections is a better chance of survival. Each antibiotic drug was consigned 
three cost components: cost of the drug and administration; cost of side 
effects; and costs of future resistance. 'No treatment' incurs no costs. The 
model worked well for decision support. Its analysis showed, yet again, that for 
moderate to severe infections, a model that does not include costs of resistance 
to future patients will always return maximum antibiotic treatment. Two major 
moral decisions are hidden in the model: how to take into account the limited 
life-expectancy and limited quality of life of old or very sick patients; and 
how to assign a value for a life-year of a future, unnamed patient vs. the 
present, individual patient.

